The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Monday, January 26, 2004 				 A slice of India
																								Calcuttans can now savour the flavours of rural India sitting in the heart of the city, thanks to Sisir Utsav 2004. Hosted by Eastern Zonal Cultural Centre (EZCC), this fair has been organised primarily to promote and popularise folk music and dances of the various regions of the country. The festival features a number of colourful dances from Assam (Bihu by Mukut Borah and his troupe today, other folk dances by Purbarang of Guwahati on January 27 and 28), folk dances from Goa (Samai, Phugdi and Deepak, today, picture above); Jharkhand (Karma by Prem Bhagat and his troupe today and on January 27, 29, 30 and 31); Manipur (Lai Haraoba and other dances on January 28, 29 and 31); Meghalaya on January 27 and 28; Nagaland on January 27, 28, 29 and 31; and Orissa (Chaiti Ghoda presented by Sangeet Kala Sansad of Cuttack district today and also on January 27, 29, 30 and 31). Another added attraction is the crafts fair (at 2 pm on all days), a window shoppers paradise. The ambiance of the food festival, running concurrently with the fair, is a gourmets ultimate dream-come-true experience. 																								When: Till January 31; 6 pm																								Where: Bharatiyam Cultural Multiplex, IB 201, Salt Lake
